<h2>Overview</h2>

<p>During my time at Phreesia, I worked on their digital patient check-in product, which included a pain scale questionnaire where patients could indicate where they were experiencing pain on a diagram of the body. Data showed that 7% of patients were abandoning the check-in process at this section (the highest drop-off rate in the entire flow). While investigating the cause, I found the body diagram was completely unusable for people who rely on a keyboard or screen reader to access the web because the body diagram had no tab stops or text alternatives. The fix required navigating a business constraint that complicated the most straightforward solution, and researching a design pattern I hadn't used before. The result was a 3.4% reduction in drop-off. Meaningful, but not yet addressing the entire 7% abandonment. The body diagram was one barrier among several we identified in that section.</p>

<h2>Problem</h2>

<p>The organization identified that 7% of patients were abandoning their check-in at the pain scale section. Because that number came from an antiquated platform, we had limited data and weren't able to see exactly which page of the five-page section was driving that drop-off. A prior usability test I had conducted with UserZoom participants of a standard check-in flow hadn't surfaced any obvious barriers.</p>

<p>When I spent some time investigating this section more closely, the problem was obvious. The page required patients to click using their mouse or tap with their finger on the image of a body diagram where they were experiencing pain. However, this interaction was a complete barrier for any patient who (A) can't use a mouse or finger, and instead navigates using a keyboard or other type of assistive technology, or (B) uses a screen reader to navigate the page. The image had no meaningful text alternative for screen readers to announce what it was displaying and no tab stops for keyboard focus.</p>

<blockquote class="pull-quote" role="note">
  <p>"For any patient navigating with a keyboard or assistive technology, this was a complete barrier."</p>
</blockquote>

<p>This hadn't been caught before because accessibility wasn't on the organization's radar. Getting a fix prioritized required my product manager and I to escalate to leadership. I wasn't sure how that conversation would go.</p>

