<h2>Process</h2>

<p>While my product manager handled making the business case with leadership, with support from our legal team who were pushing for a quick fix, I started exploring what a solution might look like. My instinct was to change as little as possible on the front end: make the interaction keyboard-accessible, add tab stops to the existing image, write patient-friendly text alternatives for each body region, and handle focus indication within the existing visual design. A more significant alternative, like replacing the diagram with progressive disclosure dropdown lists, felt like too large of a departure from the initial experience.</p>

<p>It was around this time that we received approval from leadership to prioritize a fix, with one constraint: the ability for patients to select a custom, specific point on the diagram needed to stay. They believed that ability was clinically valuable. After discussing implementation options with my lead engineer, he informed me that free-form point selection on an image is genuinely difficult to make keyboard-accessible. We wouldn't be able to allow both precise selection via mouse/tap and a keyboard/screen reader friendly experience in one unified interaction. This is what led me toward an accessibility mode toggle.</p>

<div class="callout">
  <p class="callout__label">Business constraint</p>
  <p>The business needed custom point selection to stay. That ruled out the simplest accessible solution.</p>
</div>

<p>At first, I wasn't comfortable with this. A separate mode felt like the kind of thing that quietly breaks with no one noticing or gets deprioritized in future iterations. But I also knew I couldn't make that call based on my own assumptions. I needed to hear from people who actually use a keyboard or screen reader. UserZoom's participant pool made this nearly impossible. The incidence rate for finding keyboard-only and screen reader users was under 1%. I managed one interview, but that wasn't enough to go on.</p>

<blockquote class="pull-quote" role="note">
  <p>"The accessible version couldn't do everything the original could. That was the constraint we couldn't design our way out of."</p>
</blockquote>

<p>So I took to Reddit: r/accessibility, r/blind, and r/webaccess. It felt scrappy, but the alternative was proceeding with barely any validation at all. In my post I disclosed that I was a designer working on a healthcare product and asked how people felt about accessibility mode toggles. The consistent message was that a toggle was acceptable: it was a interaction difference, not a wholesale separate experience. That reframe helped, even if our specific constraint meant the line wasn't quite that clean.</p>

<div class="callout">
  <p class="callout__label">Key insight</p>
  <p>Respondents were comfortable with accessibility mode toggles as long as they were easy to find.</p>
</div>

<p>From there, the decisions became more granular. Where should the toggle live? Proximity felt important since the toggle would only affect the body diagram at this point. Placing it at the start of the entire check-in process felt disconnected. Ultimately, I put it below the section heading, but above the body diagram interaction so it would be easier to discover. What should the label say? The goal was to set clear expectations. I wrote some initial options and consulted with a copywriter from another team to refine them. I made the final call on the label.</p>

<figure>
  <div style="background: var(--color-bg-alt); height: 360px; display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center; border-radius: 8px; color: var(--color-text-muted);">[ Accessibility toggle ]</div>
  <figcaption>The accessibility mode toggle as it appears on page load — positioned above the body diagram to aid discoverability.</figcaption>
</figure>

<p>I brought in one of the company's clinical information specialists to help decide on the correct tab order and number of focusable regions on the body diagram. We started with over 100 potential regions. They helped narrow this down to 40 as well as come up with patient-friendly text alternatives for each. Notably, this team raised something I hadn't considered: whether the patient-facing label and the label recorded in the electronic health record could differ? For example, a patient hears " left wrist" but the electronic health record receives "left carpal region." My architect confirmed this was possible. The custom point offered more spatial precision: a patient could indicate exactly where on their wrist they felt pain. The accessible version traded that precision for something clinically useful in a different way: a labelled region the system could record automatically, removing a step for the provider.</p>

<div class="callout">
  <p class="callout__label">Tradeoff</p>
  <p>The custom point offered more spatial precision. The accessible version traded that for a labelled region the system could record automatically.</p>
</div>

<p>For the focus indicator, the browser's default rectangle alone wasn't enough to communicate which body region was active, especially in areas where body regions were awkwardly shaped. To help, I created 40 custom vector images, one for each focusable region, that filled with color on focus, making it visually clear which area was selected. The browser's default focus indicator remained alongside the svg fill rather than be replaced by it. </p>

<figure>
  <div style="background: var(--color-bg-alt); height: 360px; display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center; border-radius: 8px; color: var(--color-text-muted);">[ Before/after focus indicator ]</div>
  <figcaption>Left: the browser's default focus rectangle on its own. Right: the same region with the custom SVG colour fill added to clarify which body area is active.</figcaption>
</figure>

<p>At this time, Figma's prototyping abilities were not accessible, so I had to wait until my engineering team had a workable proof of concept to test with real users. Getting there required making a case to my manager to use UserZoom's white glove service to recruit keyboard-only users. The sessions confirmed that the tab order was predictable and knowing which region had focus was clear. Two things weren't working.</p>

<p>First, patients didn't immediately notice the accessibility toggle when they arrived on the page. Leadership was concerned that sighted mouse users might accidentally enable it. I pushed back — at this point in the questionnaire, most patients are focused on finishing, not exploring unfamiliar controls. And most people know whether they need accessibility features. That's an assumption, but I still think it was a reasonable one. Second, once the toggle was enabled, it wasn't obvious what had changed on the page. Without a clear signal, patients had to figure out on their own that the body diagram could now be navigated with their keyboard.</p>

<p>Given where we were in the timeline, I addressed both with light-touch fixes: repositioning the toggle to the left to follow a natural scanning pattern, and adding a toast message on activation to let patients know the body diagram could now be navigated using their keyboard. I would have liked more time to test whether those changes actually worked, but that testing didn't happen before release.</p>

<figure>
  <div style="background: var(--color-bg-alt); height: 360px; display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center; border-radius: 8px; color: var(--color-text-muted);">[ Toast notification ]</div>
  <figcaption>The toggle in its enabled state, with the toast message confirming the body diagram can now be navigated using a keyboard.</figcaption>
