<h2>Solution</h2>

<p>The shipped solution added an accessibility mode toggle to the body diagram page within the pain scale section. When enabled, patients could navigate approximately 40 labelled body regions using their keyboard, with a visible focus indicator and screen-reader-friendly text for each region. The ability to select a custom point remained available for patients not using accessibility mode.</p>

<figure>
  <div style="background: var(--color-bg-alt); height: 360px; display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: center; border-radius: 8px; color: var(--color-text-muted);">[ Redesigned body diagram with accessibility mode enabled ]</div>
  <figcaption>The body diagram with accessibility mode enabled. The SVG overlay highlights the active region on focus; screen readers announce the patient-friendly label for each.</figcaption>
</figure>

<p>Once implemented, drop-off during this section fell by 3.4%. That's a meaningful improvement, but it leaves the remaining 4% unaccounted for. The body diagram was one friction point in a multi-question section. I identified several other opportunities worth addressing: the repetitive flow for adding multiple pain points, the ambiguity of some pain-type labels, and an unclear severity scale interaction.</p>

<p>We also saw average time spent on this section increase by about 20 seconds. Leadership flagged it, which we'd anticipated. Navigating through 40 regions takes longer than tapping a single point on an image and they accepted the explanation. That was the cost of doing it right.</p>

<h2>Reflection</h2>

<p>The decision I'd love to revisit is the choice to skip usability testing with screen reader users. The choice was made due to limited research credits for additional white glove recruitment. I was the only person who tested the screen reader experience. Because I only had a Macbook, I was only able to test using VoiceOver. I have no idea how the experience holds up with other popular screen readers like NVDA or JAWS. Knowing screen reader behavior varies significantly across browser and assistive technology combinations, I knew those nuances weren't something I would catch myself. So without that testing, we were essentially leaving it to real patients to find the gaps. If I had another chance, I'd push harder for screen reader testing as a condition of release, not a nice-to-have. The credit cost was real, but the risk was spending significant time and effort on an accessibility fix that didn't actually work for the people it was meant to serve.</p>